commit.message:
Improve PDF dicts serialization stability

This should help with document serialization stability. Order of entries
in a dict is irrelevant so it should not have any bearing on document
identity.

PS: PDF spec uses logical order of entries in examples but Adobe Acrobat
actually sorts entries alphabetically. For instance, the most logically
important entry `/Type` is often the last.

commit.message: Remove leading and limit change to rise
Add rise and leading to the set of text state operator helpers

Fix serialisation of literal strings and Time

According to the PDF spec, a literal string may contain any character
except unbalanced parentheses ( and ) and the backslash. To make it
easy, these three characters need to be escaped.

Additionally, the carriage return needs to be escaped as \\r, i.e.
a backslash followed by the letter r. If it is not escaped, a single
\r would be read as \n according to the spec. And a backslash followed
by carriage return is ignored when read. So the only way to do it is
to use \\r.

commit.message:
Update text operator state to be resilient against exceptions in blocks

Before this PR, exceptions raised in the blocks wrapping text operator state changes could corrupt the document state.  If the operator state is being set to a value different than the current document state, and the block raises an exception, then both the in-memory variable and the in-PDF page start were corrupted.  This PR adds ensure blocks to guarantee that the value of both the in-memory and the PDF state is appropriately reset.

This PR also adds some basic specs for text_rendering_mode, as those specs were absent and this PR should test the error case for that operator state as well.
